     <body>
     <div type="poem">
   <head>To Master Hannay.</head>
   <lg>
      <l>THy happy Husband shewes thy high ingine,</l>
      <l>Whose Muse such method in her measures can,</l>
      <l>The matter shewes thy manners are diuine;</l>
      <l>Thy practiz'd vertues shewes thou art this Man:</l>
      <l>I halfe enuie that highly blessed Maid,</l>
      <l>Whose happy lot shall be to linke with thee,</l>
      <l>And well-nie wish that Nature had me made</l>
      <l>A woman; so I such one's wife might be:</l>
      <l>Detraction is distraught thy lines to see,</l>
      <l>And sweld with enuy, can no words bring forth,</l>
      <l>Her basenesse cannot paralell thy worth.</l>
      <l>Which still shall liue vnto eternity:</l>
      <l>For after Ages reading of thy verse,</l>
      <l>Shall decke with Lawrell thy adored herse.</l>
   </lg>
   <p>
      <hi>P. T.</hi>
   </p>
</div>
